A symmetry of a geometric figure is a rearrangement of the figure preserving the arrangement of its sides and vertices as well as its distances and angles.  A map from the plane to itself preserving the symmetry of an object is called a rigid motionRigid motion.  For example, if we look at the rectangle in Figure, it is easy to see that a rotation of 180^{\circ} or 360^{\circ} returns a rectangle in the plane with the same orientation as the original rectangle and the same relationship among the vertices.  A reflection of the rectangle across either the vertical axis or the horizontal axis can also be seen to be a symmetry.  However, a 90^{\circ} rotation in either direction cannot be a symmetry unless the rectangle is a square.









